                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d277">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">722.2315/2489: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Ambassador in Peru</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Norweb</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1941-11-02T03:00:00-05:00"
                            >November 2, 1941—3 a.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>439. From the Under Secretary. Your 584, October 31, 4 p.m., and Department’s
                    438, November 2, 2 a.m.<note n="37" xml:id="d277fn1">Latter not printed.</note>
                    The Department of course considers it in the highest degree desirable for you
                    and your Argentine and Brazilian colleagues to continue your conversations with
                    the Peruvian Minister for Foreign Affairs so as to make it evident that the
                    representatives of the powers which have tendered their good offices are
                    operating as intermediaries in the prospective negotiations. Your informal
                    discussions with the Minister of Ecuador are obviously of great value as
                    supplementary thereto. [Welles.]</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Hull</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
